AGI - Armenia has returned to Azerbaijan four border villages that had seized decades ago making a fundamental step towards the normalization of relations, very bureaucratic, between the two countries. The move, which triggered prolonged protests in Armenia, is an important step in achieving a global peace agreement after years of unsuccessful talks mediated by Russia and Western countries. The two former Soviet republics fought two wars, in the 1990s and 2020, for the control of the separatist region of <a href="https://www.agi.it/tag/nagorno-karabakh/">Nagorno-Karabakh</a>>. Azerbaijan regained it last year with a lightning offensive, ending three decades of Armenian separatist rule on the enclave and pushing more than 100,000 residents to flee to Armenia.&nsp; The disastrous defeat of Erevan has caused a split with his historic ally, Russia, that Armenia accuses of not defending her against the Azores threats despite the obligations of a security treaty.&nbsp; After months of diplomatic tension, Moscow declared on Friday that he recalled his ambassador for "consultations". The spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs Maria Zakharova did not provide a reason for the call, which is typically seen in diplomatic circles as an extreme step in the face of the worsening of the links between the two governments.
&nbsp;
The Armenian security service confirmed that its border guards have taken new positions in the eastern part of the country, following a demarcation agreement of the borders recently negotiated with Baku and giving the four villages to the control of Azerbaijan.&nbsp; The Deputy Prime Minister of Azerbaijan, Shahin Mustafayev>, announced separately that the border guards of his country assumed control of the four settlements. The Armenian Prime Minister, Nikol Pashinyan>, agreed to return the four abandoned villages, seized in the 1990s, as part of the efforts to ensure a lasting peace agreement. In a television statement, he said that the new line of the border, always unstable, with Azerbaijan "is the only guarantee for the very existence of the Armenian Republic within its legitimate and internationally recognized frontier".
&nbsp;
<div </div
<em> &nbsp;Karen Minasyan / Afptv / Afp</em>
&nbsp;
<h2> Residents' complaints
At the beginning of the month the two countries agreed the new demarcation of 12.7 km&nbsp; of their border, with the return of the centers Baghanis Ayrum, Ashaghi Askipara, Kheyrimli and Ghizilhajili.
To Azerbaijan. Pashinyan greeted the agreement as "very important" for Armenia's sovereignty and said that "it brings our security and stability to a new level". The territory ceded by Erevan is of strategic importance to Armenia, which has no outlets on the sea, because it controls sections of a vital highway also for Georgia. Armenian residents of nearby settlements argue that the move could cut them off from the rest of the country and accuse Pashinyan of unilaterally surrendering the territory without obtaining anything in return. Pashinyan said Armenia will build new roads in the area in the coming months.
