to AGI - Israel "immediately" the operation to Rafah, in the extreme south of Gaza, keep the passage open to the border with Egypt to bring in aid in the Strip, and allow the entry of investigators into the Palestinian enclave. It is the order issued by the International Court of Justice (Icj) against the Jewish State, again accused by South Africa. For the judges of the UN court at the Hague, the humanitarian situation in the Strip has worsened and Rafah has become "disastrous". The measures implemented by Israel in these months "do not fully address the consequences of the changed situation", said the head of the court Nawaf Salam, who asked the Jewish State to provide a report on the new measures within a month>.&nbsp; On January 26, the court ordered Israel to do everything possible to prevent acts of genocide during the military operation in Gaza, and in March he had pledged to ensure the "wide-scale unhindered supply of humanitarian aid". The ICJ also called for the "immediate and unconditional liberation" of Israeli hostages held in Gaza by Hamas. Precisely the lack of correlation between this request to Hamas and the order to Israel to stop the invasion of Rafah was stigmatized by Israeli opposition leader Yair Lapid who spoke of "moral disaster" of judges.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
